{"rendered": {"description": {"raw": "This is a backport of pull request #1038 to the gazebo 2.2 branch.\r\n\r\nIt is mainly an exercise of keeping ABI stable using available mechanisms. In this case, I've used a static data member (the only type that can keep ABI stable) to declare the mutex. That implies that the mutex will be shared by all the instances of the Gripper class, but I don't see a major problem with that more than losing performance, which it is probably better than a segfault.", "markup": "markdown", "html": "<p>This is a backport of <a href=\"#!/osrf/gazebo/pull-requests/1038/protect-parallel-write-read-access-to\" rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"ap-connect-link\">pull request #1038</a> to the gazebo 2.2 branch.</p>\n<p>It is mainly an exercise of keeping ABI stable using available mechanisms. In this case, I've used a static data member (the only type that can keep ABI stable) to declare the mutex. That implies that the mutex will be shared by all the instances of the Gripper class, but I don't see a major problem with that more than losing performance, which it is probably better than a segfault.</p>", "type": "rendered"}, "title": {"raw": "Backport Gripper fix to 2.2 branch (->2.2)", "markup": "markdown", "html": "<p>Backport Gripper fix to 2.2 branch (-&gt;2.2)</p>", "type": "rendered"}}, "type": "pullrequest", "description": "This is a backport of pull request #1038 to the gazebo 2.2 branch.\r\n\r\nIt is mainly an exercise of keeping ABI stable using available mechanisms. In this case, I've used a static data member (the only type that can keep ABI stable) to declare the mutex. That implies that the mutex will be shared by all the instances of the Gripper class, but I don't see a major problem with that more than losing performance, which it is probably better than a segfault.", "links": {"decline": {"href": "https://api.bitbucket.org/2.0/repositories/osrf/gazebo/pullrequests/1043/decline"}, "diffstat": {"href": "https://api.bitbucket.org/2.0/reposito